body:
@nblumhardt We are looking at the Serilog.Sinks.Seq sink and have modified it to accept a `LoggingLevelSwitch` instead of a `LogEventLevel` so the min level that is returned from the HTTP call to the Seq server can be exposed to the rest of the application rather than being hidden inside the internal `_minimumAcceptedLevel` variable. 

Our specific use case is that we are exposing a route in our MVC website so that web clients can log from javascript. We then use the website and the Seq Sink to forward this information on to the internal Seq Server. We do however want to expose that min level back to the javascript so that they only post the log events over the network back to the server if the level is greater than the min level as configured by the Seq Server API Key. Hence we want access to that `mininumAcceptedLevel` value that the sink if using.

I was about to submit a pull request against the Seq Sink, then noticed this thread here. What are your thoughts on the `SeqSink` using a `LoggingLevelSwitch` internally instead of a `LogEventLevel` and allowing the switch to be passed in via the `SeqLoggerConfigurationExtensions.Seq()` extension method instead of the `LogEventLevel`. It's not a Serilog global solution like you are proposing here, but it suits the Seq Sink purpose.

issue.body:
An implementation for #505. Supports configuration like:

``` csharp
var fileLevel = new LoggingLevelSwitch(LogEventLevel.Warning);

var log = new LoggerConfiguration()
  .WriteTo.File("...", levelSwitch: fileLevel)
  .CreateLogger();

// Later...
fileLevel.MinimumLevel = LogEventLevel.Debug;

log.Information("This will be written to the file");
```

This is a **binary breaking change** for user code that calls sink configuration methods, but not for third-party sink assemblies. I don't think it justifies a "2.0" version bump, but open to ideas.

